:: Ending: Internal {"position":"2650,375","size":"100,100"}
### Ending: Internal Resolution

You decide not to go public yet.

Instead, you continue pushing the issue through internal channels.

You document your concerns, gather what evidence you can, and escalate the bug more forcefully.

Management resists at first, but the concern can no longer be quietly brushed aside.

A review is opened.

Fixes are slow, partial, and politically painful, but action is finally taken.

You keep your job.

But things are tense now.

You are no longer seen the same way by management, and some of your co-workers blame you for the fallout.

The issue is addressed.

But it comes at a cost.


:: Ending: Silence {"position":"2650,575","size":"100,100"}
### Ending: Silence

You decide not to take the issue any further.

Maybe the evidence is too weak.

Maybe the risk is too high.

Maybe you are not convinced whistleblowing would actually help.

So you let it go.

For a while, life at work continues as normal.

Alex seems relieved that you didn't push the issue further.

Then, weeks later, the reset issue becomes public anyway.

The company faces backlash. Investigations begin. Layoffs follow.

You tried to protect yourself by staying out of it.

In the end, silence did not spare you from the consequences.

And whatever relief Alex felt at the time doesn't last once everything comes to light.

You are left wondering whether acting sooner would have made any difference.


:: Ending: Whistleblow {"position":"2650,800","size":"100,100"}
### Ending: Whistleblower

You decide the risk is too serious to keep inside the company.

You take the issue outside.

The story goes public.

News spreads quickly about the device vulnerability and the company's data practices.

Regulators step in. Patients are notified. The company takes a major hit.

You lose your job.

Alex is affected by the fallout as well. He tells you that he is being investigated.

Your reputation in the industry becomes complicated. Some see you as principled. Others see you as a liability.

The issue is no longer hidden.

Whether the cost was worth it is something you may be asking yourself for a long time.


:: Fired With Cause {"position":"775,925","size":"100,100"}
### Game Over

Joe has always been stubborn about accepting help and would never willingly tell others because he doesn't want to be a burden. You decide to investigate to find out how he's doing.


You dive into the company's filesystem and access Joe's medical records. You're halfway through his most recent medical report when a shadow falls over your keyboard. 


''Dave:''"Find the duplication bug yet?"


You jump, nearly knocking your coffee over. It's Dave, the Engineering Manager. She isn't looking at you, she's looking at your monitor. His eyes narrow as they see the name "Joe Smith" at the top of the medical report.


''Dave:'' "That's not a log file,.... and that's User ID isn't in the ticket I gave you."


Before you can stutter out an excuse Dave reaches over and turns off your computer.


''Dave:'' "Step away from the desk. Now!"


You try to explain, telling him Joe is family and that you were just worried, but Dave’s expression doesn't change at all.


''Dave:'' "I don't care if he's your brother in law. You didn't just 'check' a file. You bypassed all our security measures to access highly sensitive Private Health Information without a clinical or technical requirement. This is a massive violation of PIPEDA and our internal data governance policy." 
-------
You are fired, your badge is deactivated, and you are escorted out of the building.


:: First Ticket {"position":"775,775","size":"100,100"}
Looks like you're all ready to go! Dave, the engineering team manager has assigned you this ticket:

"A small number of users' heart data records are being duplicated somewhere along our ingestion workflow. Here are the 3 User IDs: ...."

You dive into the database logs and begin querying the database to cross reference the User IDs. Suddenly, a name catches your attention and causes your heart to stop. 

"Joe Smith" your brother in law's name flashes across your screen alongside the "Critical" status.


It isn't related to your task at hand but you're concerned about your family member's health.
-----
([[Investigate your brother in law's data->Fired With Cause]])
([[Focus on the task at hand]])


