:: Manager Rejects Concern {"position":"1800,950","size":"100,100"}
'You decide to bring your findings to your manager.

You explain what you observed, walking them through the reset behavior and your concerns about potential inaccuracies.

They listen, but their expression doesn't change.

''Manager:'' "So you're not sure this actually affects real devices?"

You hesitate.

You explain that it might — but you don't have enough data to prove it yet.

The manager leans back.

''Manager:'' "Then we're not going to escalate this based on a maybe."

They continue.

''Manager:'' "We have deadlines. If this was critical, it would've shown up already."

There is a long pause.

 ''Manager:'' "And to be honest, even if you proved it, there's no easy fix. We designed our implants for security, not remote access. We can't just patch the hard-coded value in the hardware like we can push update our app's UI. Any hotfix would involve a physical recall, and Corazón can't survive that kind of reputation loss. I doubt we'd be able to compensate our customers by covering their surgeries. We don't have the money to cover 100,000 surgeries."

''Manager:'' "Let's just focus on your assigned work."

The conversation is over.

You return to your desk.

The issue hasn't gone away.

But now you know one thing clearly:

Management isn't interested, or they at least don't want to believe that their main product has an unfixable flaw. At has at least not without stronger evidence.

----
[[Consult to your coworkers to see if your concerns are valid->Talk to your coworkers]]
[[Talk to Alex about what happened->Talk to Alex (Low Confidence)]]
[[Drop the issue and move on->Ignore Issue]]


