:: Potential Security Vulnerability {"position":"1625,650","size":"100,100"}
As you begin working on the API for the pharmaceutical company, you start reviewing how device data is handled.

While testing, you notice something unusual in the device reset logic.

A value used during device resets is hard coded instead of being unique for each device.

At first glance, it seems like a harmless shortcut.

But something about it feels off.

You run a few more tests.

The behavior isn't consistent.

In some cases, after a reset, the device continues running with slightly altered internal states.

You pause.

If this is happening in production devices, it could lead to incorrect or uncalibrated readings — false alarms, or worse, missed heart irregularities.

You lean back in your chair.

This isn't documented anywhere.

It might just be an edge case.

Or it might be something more serious.

Right now, you're not sure.

But if your suspicion is correct, this could impact patient safety.

You glance across the office. No one else seems concerned.

Maybe no one else has noticed.

Or maybe you're just being paranoid.

Either way, this is now your problem.

----
[[Report your concerns to your manager->Manager Rejects Concern]]
[[Consult someone more experienced before taking action->Talk to your coworkers]]
[[Ignore it and continue working->Ignore Issue]]


:: Reasons to Sell User's Health Data {"position":"1250,975","size":"100,100"}
"Why are we doing this, is the company in trouble?" you bluntly ask.

The CEO sighs, dropping the corporate persona.

''CEO'' "Startups are expensive. We've expanded too quickly and the venture capitalist money is running out. Our charity program is also bleeding us dry. The pharmaceutical company is also willing to make a charitable 'donation' that would fund another 10,000 low-income patients."

''Manager'' "If you're worried about the legality, don't be. We snuck a clause into the Terms & Conditions months ago that allows for third party data transfers. It's perfectly legal as long as we anonymize the data."

''CEO'' "Try to think about it as keeping our mission alive"
