:: Talk to Alex (High Confidence) {"position":"2250,400","size":"100,100"}
Later that day, you find Alex and ask if he has a minute.

You explain the reset issue and what your co-workers told you.

Alex listens, his expression tightening.

''Alex:'' "So it's real."

You nod.

''Alex:'' "Maybe not always, but real enough to matter."

He exhales slowly.

''Alex:'' "This is a serious issue. Management will not like it. And if you go outside the company, there's no taking it back."

There is brief pause as he considers his words.

''Alex:'' "I'm not telling you to stay silent. Just be sure you're ready for what comes next."

You already knew that.

But hearing it out loud makes the weight of the decision clearer.

----
[[Decide what to do next->Whistleblowing Dilemma]]
[[Step back and leave it alone->Ignore Issue]]


:: Talk to Alex (Mid Confidence)

You find Alex and explain what you've discovered.

You tell him about the reset issue, and that you've already talked to Bob and Rob.

They didn't agree.

Bob thinks it's serious. Rob doesn't.

Alex listens, frowning slightly.

''Alex:'' "…yeah, that makes this tricky."

He pauses for a moment.

''Alex:'' "I'm not really the best person to judge something like this."

''Alex:'' "If the people closer to it can't agree, I don't think I can give you a better answer."

He looks at you.

''Alex:'' "You're going to have to decide what you think this is."

There's a brief silence.

''Alex:'' "And what you're willing to do about it."

----

[[Decide what to do next->Whistleblowing Dilemma]]
[[Step back and leave it alone->Ignore Issue]]


:: Talk to Alex (Low Confidence) {"position":"2250,1200","size":"100,100"}
Later that day, you find Alex and ask if they have a minute.

You explain what you found in the reset logic, but you also admit that you are not fully sure what it means yet.

Alex listens carefully, then leans back.

''Alex:'' "So this is still a suspicion, not proof?"

You hesitate, then nod.

Alex exhales.

''Alex:'' "Then be careful."

He lowers his voice.

''Alex:'' "I'm not saying ignore it forever. But if you go to management or outside the company with a maybe, there's no way they will believe you."

Alex folds his arms.

''Alex:'' "People here are already stressed. The pharmaceutical deal, deadlines, investors... it's a sensitive period right now."

He glances around the office.

''Alex:'' "And if this blows up, it won't just hit you. You know that, right?"

You do know.

Alex was the one who referred you here.

If you act too early, you may be risking both your position and your friendship for something you are not even fully certain about.

Still, the possibility of patient harm is hard to ignore.

----
[[Rethink your options carefully->Whistleblowing Dilemma]]
[[Drop the issue for now->Ignore Issue]]


:: Talk to Bob {"position":"2050,575","size":"100,100"}
You walk them through what you've found.

They don't interrupt.

When you finish, they sit quietly for a moment.

''Bob:'' "You're right to be concerned."

They turn their monitor toward you and pull up some internal logs.

''Bob:'' "It's subtle. That's why it slipped through."

They point at a pattern.

Bob: "There is definitely a pattern because of the hard coded value."

''Bob:'' "This won't break every device. But hackers could theoretically use it to manipulate the data signals so that the readings could be off."

You feel your stomach tighten.

''Bob:'' "This should've been investigated properly."

They pause.

''Bob:'' "But if you bring this up now, you're going to need to be very sure of what you're saying."

(if: (history:) does not contain "Talk to Rob")[
    ''Bob:'' "You might also want to run this by Rob."
]

You now have more confidence.

But also more responsibility.

